Priority, with nice and renice.

Linux's scheduler shares see-pee-you time among all the processes that are ready to run, and by default everything gets a fair slice. When you want to tilt that balance, you adjust a process's nice value. The range runs from minus twenty, the highest priority, all the way up to nineteen, the lowest, with zero as the default. It feels backwards at first: a higher nice number means lower priority. The trick is to read nice as how willing a process is to yield. A process at nice nineteen is extremely willing to step aside for others, while one at nice minus twenty is selfish and grabs the see-pee-you for itself.

There is an important permission rule here. Only root can decrease a nice value and so raise a process's priority. Any ordinary user can increase the nice value, lowering the priority of their own processes, but never the reverse. That stops users from quietly handing themselves more see-pee-you than they are entitled to.

To start a command at a chosen niceness, you prefix it with the nice command and the dash n flag; raising the priority into negative territory needs sudo. To change the priority of a process that is already running, you use renice, pointing it at a process I-D, or at all of a particular user's processes. There is also a separate knob for disk activity, called i-o-nice, which sets input-output priority independently of see-pee-you priority, with an idle class that only does input-output when nothing else needs the disk. The two combine beautifully for a heavy backup you do not want to disturb production: run it at the gentlest nice value and in the idle input-output class, and it quietly soaks up only the spare capacity. For exam purposes, know nice and renice well, and treat i-o-nice as a useful extra.
